bled the law, terrified society, ignited juridical and parliamentary debates, and mobilized citizens. Bringing together archival and media materials with the victims’ accounts and diverse forms of cultural response, the book examines ransom kidnapping through the lenses of historiography, law, literary criticism, trauma studies, phenomenology, and political philosophy. Ransom Kidnapping in Italy traces how and at what price Italians became aware of living in a country that was being blackmailed by criminal organizations that arguably jeopardized the nation even more than terrorism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aKidnappingzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrganized crimezItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aRansomzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aCalabria.  aCosa Nostra.  aItalian film.  aSardinian banditry.  acaptivity.  akidnapping in Italy.  amafia.  amemory and testimony.  aorganized crime.  aransom kidnapping.  aterrorism.  atrauma and violence.  a’Ndrangheta.40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754688540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487546885423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487546885/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles